---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="One shared core, many wrappers"
  description="A QSC Atlas commentary on the fragmentation of the post-quantum transition, and how it is governed through a network of expectations rather than a central authority."
>
  <div class="container commentary">
    <p class="kicker">QSC Atlas commentary</p>
    <h1>One shared core, many wrappers</h1>
    <p class="standfirst prose">
      Why the post-quantum transition is fragmenting, and how it is governed all the same.
    </p>

    <p class="prose">
      One set of algorithms now sits underneath almost every national plan for post-quantum
      cryptography. When a United States federal agency published three standards in August 2024, a
      contested question became a settled technical fact, and within months those choices were in
      European certification catalogues, in national guidance from Paris to Bonn, and in the browsers
      shipping to the world. The core is shared. What surrounds it is not.
    </p>

    <h2>The wrappers: an instrument cascade</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The same algorithms arrive wrapped in very different instruments. In the European Union they are
      becoming binding through NIS2 and DORA and, from December 2027, the Cyber Resilience Act, though
      rarely by name. The obligation is carried by an undefined phrase, state of the art, whose
      cryptographic content is supplied by an interpretive layer of certification guidance that sits
      between legislation and practice. Elsewhere the same core is wrapped in soft national roadmaps,
      and across much of the world in nothing at all. What an organisation must do depends less on the
      mathematics, which is common, than on the jurisdiction it operates in, which is not. This is the
      instrument cascade: from an undefined legal standard down to a de facto migration obligation,
      with the operative rule written in the interpretive layer rather than the statute.
    </p>

    <h2>The clocks diverge</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The timetables fragment as sharply as the instruments. The European Union coordinates to 2030 and
      2035; France works to a phased, not-earlier-than schedule; the United States gates procurement
      through executive deadlines, one of which moved backwards in June 2025 when an order removed a
      post-quantum procurement requirement; China runs a separate SM-series track. The same migration
      therefore runs to different clocks in different places, and the deadlines are not simply
      forecasts. They are coordination devices.
    </p>

    <h2>Governing by expectation</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      This is where the transition is most unusual. Its governance runs on expectations rather than on
      an observed threat. Climate governance also coordinates through shared projections, but there the
      danger is visible: temperatures rise, ice retreats. Quantum-safe governance has no such
      observable; the cryptographically relevant quantum computer has not arrived, and may not for
      years. The deadlines do their work anyway, because expectations are performative. They cascade
      vertically, a revised hardware estimate registering at once in Washington's gates and Brussels'
      milestones, and they align horizontally, as when four national agencies co-signed a single
      position in January 2024 that confined quantum key distribution to niche uses and named
      post-quantum migration the priority. Coordination happens without a coordinator.
    </p>

    <h2>The failure mode is congestion, not absence</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      A network of expectations can fail, and its failure mode is congestion rather than a missing
      authority. The financial sector already faces DORA, national supervisors, G7 guidance and
      sectoral roadmaps at once, and the result is deferral: ENISA finds only a small share of European
      stakeholders have begun to migrate. The answer is not necessarily a central authority. It is to
      make the state of the transition common knowledge, who stands where, on which instrument, to what
      clock, which is the case the CEPS Task Force made for a public-private migration observatory under
      ENISA. It is also, in a smaller way, what this Atlas is for.
    </p>

    <p class="prose close">
      One shared core, many wrappers, held loosely together by a network of expectations. The Atlas
      maps the wrappers, country by country, so the fragmentation can at least be read.
    </p>

    <p class="attribution">
      A QSC Atlas commentary, drawing on the CEPS Task Force on Strengthening the EU Transition to a
      Quantum-Safe World (2025). <a href="/methodology">How the Atlas classifies countries &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

